      <h2>What Is a Virtual Power Plant?</h2>
      <p>
        A Virtual Power Plant (VPP) connects hundreds or thousands of home battery systems into a single coordinated network. When the electricity grid needs extra power — during peak demand, heatwaves, or supply shortfalls — your battery discharges stored energy back to the grid. In return, you get paid.
      </p>
      <p>
        You're not building a power plant. You already have one — your solar panels and battery. A VPP lets you trade that stored energy when it's most valuable, and earn money for doing it.
      </p>

      <h2>The Problem With Most VPP Programs</h2>
      <p>
        Most VPP programs are run by your electricity retailer. That means <strong>they</strong> decide when to charge and discharge your battery — and they do it to suit themselves, not you. Retailers buy and sell energy on the wholesale market, and when they control your battery, they can capitalise on price swings at your expense.
      </p>
      <p>
        You signed up thinking you'd earn extra from your battery. Instead, your retailer is using it as their own trading asset.
      </p>

      <h2>Powston VPP Self-Control</h2>
      <p>
        We integrate <strong>Powston</strong> — a VPP platform that puts you back in control. With Powston, your battery trades on the wholesale energy market according to <strong>your best interests</strong>, not your retailer's. There's no conflict of interest. No one else is deciding when to charge or discharge your battery to pad their own margins.
      </p>
      <p>
        Powston works across major Australian electricity retailers including Red Energy, Origin, Alinta Energy, Tango Energy, Energy Australia, GloBird Energy, Powershop, Amber Electric, Engie, and 1st Energy — so you're not locked into a single provider.
      </p>

      <h2>How It Works</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Solar charges your battery</strong> — during the day, your solar panels generate electricity and charge your home battery as normal</li>
        <li><strong>You use what you need</strong> — your home draws from the battery first, reducing what you buy from the grid</li>
        <li><strong>Powston trades on your behalf</strong> — when wholesale prices spike, Powston automatically exports your stored energy at the best available rate</li>
        <li><strong>You earn the difference</strong> — you receive payments based on the actual wholesale price, not a fixed feed-in tariff set by your retailer</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        The entire process is automated. You don't need to watch the market or make decisions — Powston handles the trading, and your battery recharges from solar the next day.
      </p>

      <h2>Intelligent Load Shifting</h2>
      <p>
        Alongside VPP trading, we configure intelligent load shifting through the <strong>Sigenergy app</strong>. This automatically runs your appliances at the right time using the cheapest available energy — so you use more of your own solar, reduce what you buy from the grid, and keep more energy available for VPP trading when prices are high.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each automation can be set to one of three operating modes:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Surplus PV Only</strong> — the appliance only runs when there's excess solar production. For example, your electric hot water service turns on when solar excess is greater than 2 kW. If solar dips during startup, Battery Boost temporarily supplements from the battery to keep the appliance running
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Ready by Period</strong> — you set a run time and a deadline, and the system schedules the appliance to finish on time using the cheapest energy available. For example, the dishwasher runs for a minimum of 2 hours and finishes before 3:00 PM
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Battery Level Control</strong> — the appliance runs based on your battery's state of charge. For example, your air conditioner turns on when the battery is above 95% and turns off when it drops to 70% — using energy that would otherwise be exported at a low feed-in rate
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The result: your home uses solar energy first, your battery stays charged for high-value VPP events, and your appliances run without you having to think about it.
      </p>

      <h2>What You Earn</h2>
      <p>
        VPP earnings depend on market conditions, but the advantage of Powston is that you trade at <strong>wholesale rates</strong> — which spike well above standard feed-in tariffs during peak demand. Typical returns include:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Wholesale energy payments</strong> — you're paid the actual market rate for each kWh exported, not a flat feed-in tariff</li>
        <li><strong>Peak event bonuses</strong> — during extreme demand events (heatwaves, grid shortfalls), wholesale prices can spike dramatically, and your battery exports at those rates</li>
        <li><strong>Reduced grid purchases</strong> — intelligent load shifting means you buy less from the grid, compounding your savings</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Combined with solar self-consumption and smart load shifting, VPP participation can significantly shorten your battery payback period.
      </p>

      <h2>Who Can Join?</h2>
      <p>
        If you have a solar and battery system (or are getting one installed), you're likely eligible. The main requirements are:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>A compatible home battery system (we install VPP-ready systems as standard)</li>
        <li>Internet connection for the battery to communicate with the Powston platform</li>
        <li>An electricity retailer supported by Powston (most major retailers are covered)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Victorian homeowners are well-positioned for VPPs — the state's grid demand peaks align with when home batteries have the most stored energy. Geelong, the Surf Coast, and Bellarine Peninsula all have strong solar generation profiles that make VPP participation worthwhile.
      </p>

      <h2>VPPs and Your Home Energy System</h2>
      <p>
        A VPP works best as part of an integrated energy system. When your solar, battery, and <a href="/services/residential/home-automation">home automation</a> are managed together, the system can optimise when to store, when to use, and when to export — maximising both your savings and your VPP earnings.
      </p>
      <p>
        Our <a href="/laboratory/environmental-service-pod">Environmental Service Pod (ESP)</a> is designed for exactly this kind of coordinated operation — solar, battery, heat pump, and smart controls all working as one system, with VPP and load shifting built in.
      </p>

